name: 1-naphthaleneacetonitrile
Reason: The basic structure of naphthalene has a melting point of around 80 degrees Celsius. The introduction of an acetonitrile group (–CH2–CN) can influence this melting point. A cyano group (–CN) generally increases the polarity and may lead to an increase in the melting point due to stronger dipole-dipole interactions. However, the alkyl chain (–CH2–) being flexible and hydrophobic, could slightly lower the melting point due to a decrease in symmetry and possible disruption of packing efficiency. Estimating the effects: Naphthalene: 80, Cyano group: +20 (for increased polarity and dipole interactions), Alkyl chain: -5 (due to reduced packing efficiency and increased entropy).

Reason: The basic structure of naphthalene has a melting point of around 80 degrees Celsius. The introduction of an acetonitrile group (–CH2–CN) can influence this melting point. A cyano group (–CN) is expected to increase the melting point due to added polarity and increased dipole-dipole interactions, potentially to a larger extent because it greatly enhances the molecular rigidity and could enhance intermolecular forces. The alkyl chain (–CH2–), being flexible and hydrophobic, usually has a relatively small influence on the melting point; it could slightly reduce the melting point by disrupting crystal packing. Estimating the effects: Naphthalene: 80, Cyano group: +10 to +20 (for increased polarity and enhanced intermolecular forces), Alkyl chain: -5 to -10 (due to reduced packing efficiency). Given the actual melting point is 32.5, the predicted effects of the functional groups do not align with the empirical data. Higher polarity and rigidity alone from the cyano group do not lead to a higher melting point as initially predicted. The actual value suggests that the effect of the –CH2– group in disrupting packing efficiency is greater than the effect of the –CN group in enhancing polarity. It is possible that –CH2– disrupts the efficient packing of the naphthalene molecules more significantly than the cyano group increases the melting point, which results in the overall decrease in the melting point from the base structure of naphthalene. Re-evaluation of the effects: Naphthalene: 80, Cyano group: -10 (elevated polarity but significant impact on structural packing), Alkyl chain: -30 (strong effect on disrupting crystal packing, likely greater than initially estimated due to steric considerations and conformational flexibility).
